SUP provides software enhancements, deficiency corrections, and crypto-modernization mandates to the HH-60W fleet on an annual release cycle. DO 1 enables
yearly development, test and fielding of Deficiency Reports (DRs) to the operational fleet. SUP will not only give the warfighter the ability to rapidly fix these aging issues,
but to also implement new software capability at the direction of the MAJCOM. DO1 previously included Link 16 development and testing efforts that were transferred
to Link 16 (major thrust) for the 2027 PB. SUP also includes Radar Warning Receiver (RWR) study and software update and is supported by Training Systems,
Government Test, Civilian Payroll, Mission Planning, Other Agile updates and Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) Tax. This Program shall be reoccurring to
accomplish 5 years of agile support and software to the fleet via contract. Air Combatant Command (ACC) designated this critical to accomplish any other mandates or
specific requirements.

Gun Mount System Performance Improvement will help complete development of design enhancements, testing, and integration of gun mount components needed to
address deficiencies identified during FOT&E. New software will not be required.

Communications Block Modification includes Joint Tactical Terminal-Next Generation (JTT-NG) and Hybrid SATCOM upgrades. A recent CRH decision to add Link 16
to Communications Block Modification will be updated in the next R-Documentation submission. The JTT-NG project will replace the ENTR V4 Radio system with the
JTT-NG. New software will be developed and integrated to make the system work with the platform. Hybrid SATCOM integrates high bandwidth Beyond Line of Site
(BLOS) data transfer capability in parallel with existing line of site SATCOM capabilities, including installing the Hybrid SATCOM system (transceiver and amplifier units
with their trays), and all necessary connectors and cables. New software will be developed and integrated to make the system work with the platform.

Other Programs include DVES which significantly reduces operational risk in all HH-60W regimes of flight, especially in-route navigation and terminal area operations
in unprepared operational locations where the combat rescue mission is performed. A DVES material and technical solution to the DoW's #1 flight rotary wing flight risk,
reduces operator workload, increases ability to operate in limited visibility conditions, and reduces mishaps saving lives and equipment. Link 16 test and development,
which was previously done under DO1, will now be a major thrust (Link 16) and progress to hardware updates. AIRCM is another program planned.

This funding also supports Training Systems, Support Equipment, Initial Spares, Operation Site Activation, Program Support Costs (PSC) activities, Other Government
Costs (OGC), EOIR completion costs, various studies and analysis, upgrades, future HH-60W planning activities, and resolution of Diminishing Manufacturing Sources /
Material Shortages (DMSMS) and /or obsolescence issues. DMSMS activities may include, but are not limited to, bridge buys, life of type buys, buys to protect
production schedule, and engineering efforts for redesign.

The HH-60W program budget request also supports innovation activities to include testing, data migrator support teams, integrated master plans, studies, analyses,
requirements definition, and quick-reaction capability prototypes /demonstrations to accelerate planning for technology transition, technology insertion and future
acquisition programs. Planned work includes program testing and development, data migration support, effects testing, development of baseline integrated master plans
and mission planning system analysis.

This requirement supports performance of a full financial audit as required by title 10 U.S.C. Chapter 9A, Sec 240-D.



